In Doxygen inner groups can be created by adding groups inside groups, or by using the \ingroup keyword. A few examples to clarify the possibilities:

```
/** @defgroup groupA
 *  @ingroup nonDeclaredGroup
 * {
  ...
```

This generates a new group `groupA` but unless a `\defgroup nonDeclaredGroup` is added somewhere it has no effect it is not added to any group. The only reason for this example is to state this "weird" behavior. No warning are generated.

Examples of how it works (in Doxygen):

```
/** @defgroup groupA
  * @{
  */

/* Some code... */

/** @defgroup groupB
  * @{
  */

/* Some more code... */

/**
 * @}   <- this closes groupB
 */

/* Even more code... */

/**
 * @}   <- this closes groupA
 */
```

In this example inside the `groupA` XML there will be an `innergroup` element with a reference to `groupB`, because `groupB` is inside `groupA` by scope.

```
/** @defgroup groupA
  * @{
  */

/* Some code... */

/**
 * @}   <- this closes groupA
 */

/** @defgroup groupB
 *  @ingroup groupA
  * @{
  */

/* Some more code */

/**
 * @}   <- this closes groupB
 */
```

In this example inside the `groupA` XML there will be an `innergroup` element with a reference to `groupB`, because `groupB` is has an `@ingroup` command.

In those examples the inner groups are currently not automatically "loaded" by breathe, and any references to them is unresolved unless there is a explicity directive adding them, eg, `.. doxygengroup:: groupB` added in a rST filie.

Assume the following header file:

```c++
/** @defgroup my_group This is a group
 *  @{
 */

/** My enum */
typedef enum {
    SUCCESS = 0, 
    ERROR = 1, 
} my_enum_t;

typedef struct {
    int x;
} my_struct_t;

/** @} */

/** My function */
my_enum_t my_function(my_struct_t data);
```

And the following RST code:

```rst
.. doxygengroup:: my_group
   :project: example_project
   :members:
   :undoc-members:

.. doxygenfunction:: my_function
    :project: example_project
```

When looking at the generated HTML, a link from the function definition to the struct definition is created, but a link to the enum definition is not created:

![breathe](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/30600380/79635956-eb30e780-817c-11ea-97a9-c3ae78f6ba15.png)

(BTW, without the `members` and `undoc-members` options, both links are missing.)

Doxygen version 1.8.11
Python version 3.5.2

docutils==0.16
Sphinx==3.0.1
breathe==4.15.0

Hi!

First of all thanks for the project, makes writing C++ documentation a breeze!

I'm getting these warning messages when building my project:

```
...\sourpre\docs\enums.rst:8: WARNING: Duplicate declaration, sourpre::END
...\sourpre\docs\enums.rst:10: WARNING: Duplicate declaration, sourpre::END
```

Here are the relevant enums:

```c++
enum class GridStaticProperty
{
    ...
    /*! Internal. */
    END,
};

enum class WellTransientProperty
{
    ...
    /*! Internal. */
    END,
};
```

As can be seen, there are multiple `END` declarations, but I'm using [`enum classes`](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/enum-classes-in-c-and-their-advantage-over-enum-datatype/), which makes the members semantically different and type-safe, so they are not really duplicate.

My question is: should `breathe` understand that those are `enum classes` and do not generate duplicate declarations? 

If not, does anybody know a way to ignore the warnings? I ask because I like to turn warnings into errors in `sphinx-build` to catch errors, and having this false-positive warnings prevents me from doing that.

I am documenting a C++ project with Sphinx+breathe and it went well, thanks for maintaining this useful tool.
I am using the doxygen groups and the doxygengroup command to obtain a given granularity in the documentation. In addition, I would like to place some doxygen comments both in the header files and in the source of the functions. An example is given below. It is mostly based on the examples/specific/group example in breathe arbo.
Processing this with doxygen allows to see the comment "doc in source of publicFunction" in the member function documentation. However, using breathe with the following command

.. doxygengroup:: mygroup    
  :project: group    
  :content-only:    
  :members:

I cannot see this comment. Only the comments in the .h are visible. Is there any way to obtain the documentation for both the header comments and source comments?
Regards,
Sebastien

